{"pageProps":{"post":{"slug":"mkdir-linux-command","id":"66e02c5a4d1d260001ae6449","uuid":"0afb3944-0aae-4f41-a08a-17ac6cd3fa89","title":"mkdir Linux Command","html":"<p></p><p><strong><em>mkdir</em></strong> (make directory) command creates new directories</p><p>• Creates a single directory:</p><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">mkdir directory_name</code></pre><p>• Create multiple folders with one command:</p><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">mkdir directory_name1 directory_name2 directory_name3</code></pre><p>• Creates nested directories, creating any parent directories as needed.</p><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">mkdir -p /path/to/directory</code></pre>","comment_id":"66c14fd343085b0570f0d2e8","feature_image":null,"featured":false,"visibility":"public","created_at":"2024-08-18T01:35:15.000+00:00","updated_at":"2024-09-04T23:25:56.000+00:00","published_at":"2024-08-18T01:38:43.000+00:00","custom_excerpt":"<script type=\"application/json\">\n  { \"priority\": 3 }\n</script>","codeinjection_head":null,"codeinjection_foot":null,"custom_template":null,"canonical_url":null,"url":"http://localhost:2368/mkdir-linux-command/","excerpt":"<script type=\"application/json\">\n  { \"priority\": 3 }\n</script>","reading_time":0,"access":true,"comments":false,"og_image":null,"og_title":null,"og_description":null,"twitter_image":null,"twitter_title":null,"twitter_description":null,"meta_title":null,"meta_description":null,"email_subject":null,"frontmatter":null,"feature_image_alt":null,"feature_image_caption":null},"previous":{"id":"66e02c5a4d1d260001ae6436","uuid":"5885909c-1ced-4d47-a90c-6c3e3cefa2f2","title":"rmdir Linux Command","slug":"rmdir-linux-command","html":"<p></p><p>Just as you can create a folder using mkdir , you can delete a folder using <strong><em>rmdir</em></strong> :</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.45.13-AM.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"972\" height=\"268\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.45.13-AM.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.45.13-AM.png 972w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"><figcaption><span style=\"white-space: pre-wrap;\">rmdir Linux Command</span></figcaption></figure><p>The folder you delete must be empty (like dir2 directory was empty)</p><p>You can also delete multiple folders at once:</p><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">rmdir dir2 dir3  # to remove two empty directories</code></pre><p>Be careful as this command does not ask for confirmation and it will immediately remove anything you ask it to remove.</p><p>There is no <strong>bin </strong>when removing files from the command line, and recovering lost files can be hard</p><hr><blockquote>If directory is not empty then <strong>rmdir</strong> command will give error</blockquote><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.48.51-AM.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"982\" height=\"210\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.48.51-AM.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.48.51-AM.png 982w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p>To delete folders with files in them, we'll use the more generic rm command which deletes files and folders, using the -rf options:</p><pre><code class=\"language-bash\">rm -rf dir1</code></pre><h2 id=\"rm-useful-options\">rm Useful options:</h2><p><strong>• -f (force):</strong> Forces the removal of files without prompting for confirmation, even if the files are write-protected.</p><p><strong>• -r or -R (recursive):</strong> Removes directories and their contents recursively.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.58.56-AM-1.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"972\" height=\"254\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.58.56-AM-1.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-6.58.56-AM-1.png 972w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p><strong>•</strong> <strong>-i (interactive):</strong> Prompts for confirmation before each removal.</p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-image-card\"><img src=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-7.00.55-AM.png\" class=\"kg-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"974\" height=\"232\" srcset=\"http://localhost:2368/content/images/size/w600/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-7.00.55-AM.png 600w, http://localhost:2368/content/images/2024/08/Screenshot-2024-08-18-at-7.00.55-AM.png 974w\" sizes=\"(min-width: 720px) 720px\"></figure><p><strong>•</strong> <strong>-v (verbose):</strong> Displays information about what is being done during the removal process.</p><p></p><figure class=\"kg-card kg-bookmark-card\"><a class=\"kg-bookmark-container\" href=\"https://www.bmc.com/blogs/docker-101-introduction/?ref=localhost\"><div class=\"kg-bookmark-content\"><div class=\"kg-bookmark-title\">Introduction To Docker: A Beginner’s Guide</div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-description\"></div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-metadata\"><img class=\"kg-bookmark-icon\" src=\"https://s7280.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/bmc_favicon-300x300.png\" alt=\"\"><span class=\"kg-bookmark-author\">BMC Blogs</span><span class=\"kg-bookmark-publisher\">View all posts</span></div></div><div class=\"kg-bookmark-thumbnail\"><img src=\"https://s7280.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/SHipping-Containers-Cargo-Colorful_1400x700px-300x150.jpg.optimal.jpg\" alt=\"\" onerror=\"this.style.display = 'none'\"></div></a></figure>","comment_id":"66c06cbcd0323348cb7a51db","feature_image":null,"featured":false,"visibility":"public","c